##The 40th. I'm the only one left

Micro signal

Function introduction, reach consensus, create theory, make route, put forward program, establish principle

Just as after the city was shut down, many netizens began to record their own lives, which let the world know about the daily life of people in Wuhan and their many emotions in the face of the epidemic. The talk of the 40th is also creating a platform for the individual narrative to enrich the narrative of the epidemic, so that everyone can see the real Italian "anti-epidemic" life.

As the epidemic began to unfold, it was hard to see the crowds of Piazza Dell'Otto Agosto

The first time I felt the emotional impact of the outbreak was on Monday afternoon (March 9) .

Good friends at home to complete the online graduation defense, other small partners in the square to give him a surprise, I also rushed to the meeting after the net class. The normally bustling square was largely empty. Square next to the formerly bustling cafe, only a few scattered tables and chairs outside, looking forward to the passers-by's favor. Just my little friends sitting there, twos and threes, keeping their distance. It was supposed to be a joyous day, but now we were the only ones who could make it to the graduation ceremony, which was always a big deal until everyone in the city knew about it. Last Sunday's Red Zone, which divides Italy's boroughs, was a weekend away for friends, and now it's stuck there

Leaving the square to grab a bite to eat, it's hard to find a single person walking down the bustling streets of Zamboni. Only a few stores are open, close to one, see no customers, inquire about the business is still open, we six just go in.

The table had been separated from the table by a metre, the boss said, and could not be joined. So the six of US sat at three tables, about one meter from each other on opposite sides and on both sides, it's time for the POTLUCK. After a simple meal, a girl with a dog -- colored hair, eyeliner, nose studs, coveralls, and martens -- appeared to be a well-matched literary college student wandering the streets of Zamboni. She was told by her boss that her scheduled graduation party for tomorrow had been canceled because the boss had received a new policy notice that the restaurant would be closed after 18. Disappointed, the girl sighed, "where shall I go with my friends to celebrate? "? !"

Face us, smile at each other more silent silence. In just one day and one night, a whirlwind of the virus swept in from the north, scattering people and taking away the smell of life.

We had planned to celebrate all day, but the new order came so suddenly that we had to go home and prepare our own wine.

It was still a lonely street, and thanks to the liquor store that was still open, the little fellows were still cheering, as if with this bottle, all sorrows would vanish, there was wine, there were friends, there was love.

A few of us are at home to prepare, the small partner that answers the defense goes home to rest first. It's 8:30. It's 9:00 and it's not here yet. There is no sound of the past outside the window, we even near the city center, also seems to live outside the world, we really began to self-isolation it? Looks like our friend's stuck at home, wondering if he's going out.

Just as I was getting ready to go home, farewell may be the last chance to see my friends before the outbreak, here comes the man of the hour. After all, he couldn't bear to part with us.

After drinking, everyone played guitar, playing drums, humming songs, quietly listening. The world here is both lively and silent. The room was lit only by a small bright yellow lamp. Only music flowed around us in the interlaced light and shadow. In the shadow, it seemed invisible but palpable.

It was nearly twelve o'clock, and I thought I would go home and say goodbye to my friends. Although during the day we did not say, but as much as possible to save face gifts. And this moment, it seems to depend on the mood around us, we still can not help but hug goodbye.

He went downstairs to get his bike, put on his gloves and was about to set off when he saw a street "Bum" waving a bottle of wine-the landmark of the Zamboni neighborhood, characterized by a penchant for drinking and gathering, especially at night.

I involuntarily announced, "CIAO! " Hello

He wandered over and asked, "do you have a Napkin? Can I borrow one? "

I said, "yeah, I'll look for it later. "

I'm sure he knows about the restaurant ban, and we're keeping our distance. Half a meter away, all of a sudden, he said sadly: "This virus, AH, so that now the street left me alone. "

Without saying anything, I handed him the paper and said, "Buonasera. " Have a good night

He said thank you and continued to stagger along with the bottle.

What was I supposed to say, convince him to come home? Who knows if he has a home, or if his nightly drinking companions are his only companions after a lonely day.

I put on my gloves again, tightened my hat, and got on my bike and rode home.

But that "a person" , today's most sad words, always remain in my heart.
